		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Morning commets from Gordon Wrinn</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=128292" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>
<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038156.html">Basic Rules of Conduct-just answer the question</a><P>

The Basic Rules of Conduct are agreed upon when one logs in. Period. Correct?<P>

<B>Yes, that is correct.</B><P>

These rules are in place to protect players from the abuse of the Basic Rules of Conduct. Correct?<P>

<B>This is also correct.</B><P>

Those rules, when logged in and playing EQ are a contract between Verant and the subscriber. Correct?<P>

<B>Well, they are a contract between the publisher of the game (Sony Computer Entertainment America/989 Studios) and the player. Verant develops and operates the game for the publishers, who authorize us to set policy and enforce the rules of conduct.</B><P>

Are players protected by the Constitution of the United States and the First Amendment "Free Speech" or are they in a private fantasy world, governed by the basic rules of conduct put into place by Verant and agreed upon by the player?<P>

<B>The latter. EverQuest is a private service and as such is not governed by the Constitution which protects people from the government. By using our service players agree to abide by the rules of acceptable conduct that we require for continued use of our game.</b><P>

If players are protected by the rules of conduct, and players file /reports and petitions about player abuses of the basic rules of conduct, how are players to know how many /reports or petitions have been filled against an abusive player?<P>

<B>Players have no method of acquiring this information. It is for the private use of the EverQuest customers service staff. I have heard a few suggestions that we should implement something along the lines of a public Feedback system used by Ebay, but that would have the potential for abuse.</B><P>

If players and Verant are in a contractual agreement when playing EQ to play by the rules of conduct. Is Verant in breach of that contract if "abusive" players are allowed to continue to play after numerous /reports and /petitions have been filed?<P>

<B>No. We have specific rules for dealing with issues and define what exactly is entailed by the term "abusive". We typically need concrete evidence that the rules of conduct have been broken (such as a /report or the incident being witnessed by a CS rep), and then act, at our discretion, based upon the severity of the infraction.<P> 

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038612.html">Remove the Firepot Exploiters!</a><P>

To allow these early exploiters to remain bound in the FirePot room is unfair to Wizards, Druids, all melee classes, and every- one who did not receive their Kunark CD in a timely manner. It also sends the message that it is ok to exploit known bugs, as long as you do it quickly.<P>
 
<B>We really don't have the capability to move everyone out of there all at once. For those who actually are bound in the room, I don't think that it will be very long before they change their bind points voluntarily.<P> 

Also, I really don't think that it is fair to call those that bound there "exploiters". There's no reason to expect them to have known in advance that we didn't intend it to be like that.<P> 

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038805.html">Artifact? No Drop? What exactly do they mean?</a><P>

Ok. It seems fairly clear, but I've seen some things that are confusing me.<P>

<B>Here's a list of the current item tags as listed in the EverQuest ROK Manual Supplement:<P>

MAGIC ITEM: This means that the item is imbued with magic. If this item is a weapon, it will have the ability to damage creatures which can only be harmed by magic/<P> 

LORE: This means that you may only have one of these items in your possession at any one time. If you attempt to acquire another, you will not be able to pick the item up. This will check your bank account.<P>

NODROP: This means that the item cannot be traded to another player nor sold to a merchant. However, you can hand the item to an NPC, which is necessary for many quests.<P>

ARTIFACT: This means that the item is unique upon the server that you play, and that there will never be another one given out. Artifacts are usually earned through participation in dynamic quests that occur in game regularly. Artifacts however remain so rare that most people may never see one, much less own one, which is why they are called Artifacts of Great Power.<P>

A Deities name: If a deity’s name is listed upon the item, it means that only followers of that deity may equip the item or use its effects.<P> 

Just noticed that you had questions as well :)</B><P>

ARTIFACT means that there is only one of these items in the world (server) right? How could an Artifact drop from a MoB that respawns then?<P> 

<B>The item that was recently found (a paladin sword) was marked as an artifact by mistake. It will be changed the next time we do items.</B><P>

Can you give ALL No Drop items to NPC's?<P>

<B>Yes, but it's meant to be for items associated with a quest.</B><P>

If so does killing the NPC let you loot it?<P> 

<B>Nope. This was a nasty little nodrop transfer bug that we stomped sometime back.</B><P>

Giving NPCs some items does leave that item on their corpse.<P>

<B>It used to do this, I don't believe it does any longer. However it's been a while since I handed something to an NPC and later killed it :)<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038868.html">Verant's Bad Customer Service...Myth or Reality?</a><P>

There have been people on this board who have been proclaiming Verant's customer service to be terrible and, frankly, I don't see it. I've played this game for many hours over the past year and maybe I've been lucky, but I've rarely had problems with service. Here are a few observations based on my own personal experience:<P>

[Snip editorial, see link above to view.]<P>

<B>I'd like to thank you for writing this wonderful editorial. Both the positive comments and well-deserved criticisms are well received.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038871.html">Unrealistic features of Everquest</a><P>

I'll start the list with the obvious, Monsters et al can magically see and hit you through walls, floors, and ceilings.<P>

<B>Realism must sometimes be bent in the interest of gameplay, balance, and hardware requirements. Not to mention that I think that people might get upset if we got rid of magic, and everything besides lions, wolves, and bears....<P>

(Say it with me)<P>

Oh my! :)<P>

-Gordon </B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038873.html">Verant cares more about BALANCE than FUN</a><P>

Look at all the pathetic rules attached to Kunark. Spells like scale have lame rules attached to them, manaskin barely regens mana, everylevel is a hell level, can't cast your buffs on anyone below 39. Cant bind near in this zone, cant bind in that zone. Come on, you play 50 levels, only to arrive at Balance/Rulequest?<P>

<B>We don't view these two concepts as mutually exclusive ideas. We instead believe that balance is necessary in order to promote fun, and thus the longevity of the game.<P> 

If all avenues to promote "fun" were pursued without regard to balance, we believe that people would get bored with the game and quit.</B><P>

How about, If all avenues to promote balance were pursued without regard to fun, I believe that thousands of people who bought this game would quit out of frustration and leave nasty posts about Verant's "vision".<P>
 
<B>Absolutely. The door swings both ways.</B><P> 

Guess what, it's happening.<P> 

<B>But no, it's not. EQ has consistently gained subscribers every week since it was release.<P> 

One thing that I think most people understand about MMOG's is that people who leave them tend to leave because they are unhappy with something or bored. It happens, but unlike in singleplayer games where people can win them, then put them in the closet never to pick them up again all the while remembering them fondly, it's usually some event that causes people to leave MMOG's. This leads to unhappy people posting on the boards, and would happen regardless what the Vision(tm) was.<P> 

That's not to say that peoples complaints are invalid. They are far from that. Everyone has different reasons for playing these games and everyone has a reason that is at least valid to them when they quit. Though we can't apologize for the Vision(tm) itself, since it is what makes EQ what it is, we definitely apologize to those who left the game due to issues that we can all agree were bad, such as overcrowding or periods of excessive downtime.<P> 

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038874.html">ROK:The refund...</a><P>

Has anyone gotten any reply from the E-Mail that we were asked to send? I have yet to receive any confirmation of a refund, or the free month.<P>

<B>The refunds are being processed as quickly as possible and emails are being sent when that occurs. There's a fair amount involved in the whole process, such as verifying that the original order was placed and that it hasn't already been refunded. We appreciate your patience.<P>
 
-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/038928.html">The Best Dungeon Experience of my EQ Life. Thank you Verant!</a><P>

Well, tonight I took my level 10 Iksar monk into the legendary Tower of Kurn, in the Field of Bone. I knew to expect much danger, as the undead there were many levels above me, but I asked around in FoB if anyone wanted to join me in a group to fight in the tower. Many were scared, but I got a few people to come. 2 Monks, a Warrior, a Shaman, and myself. 

[Snip well written article, check link above for the entire thing.]<P>

<B>Thanks for telling the story. It's nice to read these once in a while, and also nice to hear about people "doing" dungeons.<P>
 
The aggro range is what it is due to the design of the tower. It makes the dungeon a little bit easier than we would like, but increasing it causes some really nasty trains.<P> 

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/eq-expansion/Forum1/HTML/002789.html">Abashi about spell drops, please comment.</a><P>

My question is when you removed spell drops from 51+ mobs did you forget to put it back in when kunark went live? I have yet to read about a SINGLE spell being dropped on any server from any mob.<P>

My group is almost all 53 now and we've killed 1 level 54 mob and about 10 level 53 mobs and 30-40 level 51-52 mobs and have yet to find a single spell for any class. That's just my group of 6 and none have dropped for any of the 100000+ players from what I've seen.<P>

<B>I have the EQLive team double checking the data on this now. If it's wrong, we'll get it updated. We can probably do it without dropping the servers if there's a problem, so it won't have to wait too long.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/eq-expansion/Forum1/HTML/002831.html">Exp penatly why does it still exist?</a><P>

While I knew, nearly a year ago that the path I had choosen as a Teir'Dal Shadow Knight would not be an easy at the time there where certain advantages that i *thought* out weighted the disadvantages and made the class/race combo viable long term. I have spent last year trying to catch up to my friends in level. ( I am generally out leveled 3 for 2 even getting the same exp ) The only way I found to get even close was to solo and solo a lot.<P>

<B>We haven't modified the experience curves for the live game since release. Once players enter a certain level, the experience requirements cannot be modified without causing problems.<P>

That said, we still feel that the experience requirements for the classes are justified. There really isn't an experience penalty per se. Some races take more experience than others, as do some classes. There's no penalty or bonus.<P> 

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/eq-expansion/Forum1/HTML/002842.html">Gordon question, non-whine, Iksar Faction</a><P>

Now here my question and problem, I have very little time to play, and My current machine isnt handleing Kunark the way it should. I have to dumb down the graphics completely to play over there. So I would like to move my Iksar to the main land. The question is this, is it ever possible to kill enough faction giving mobs to be none KOS in say Freeport?<P>
 
<B>Though I understand your problem, commenting on how specific factions can be modified through player actions is something that we leave up to players to figure out. I do wish you well in your quest though. Even if you can't get it up that high, the innate forage skill might help you get enough food to live on the mainland.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/eq-expansion/Forum1/HTML/002851.html">Abashi said...</a><P>

That a good example of plate looking armor that is actually chain is Rubicite... If thats the case, why can't Iksar wear rubicite?<P>

<B>Not all of the items from the old world are open to the Iksar. Some certainly will be, but they prefer to be in items that they have experience with.<P>

-Gordon</B>
</blockquote>
